fully_entered","revolutionary_war","yale_graduate"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 351"}],"burial":{"plot_notes":"Fair Haven Union Cemetery, New Haven CT. GPS: 41.31140, -72.89440.","cemetery_id":"CEM101"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00324","children_ids":["H00809","H00810","H00811","H00812","H00813","H00814","H00815","H00816","H00817","H00818","H00819","X00355"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1780,"date_month":3,"location_country":"United States"}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"military","related_id":"H00288","display_label":"Friend-compatriots in the Revolutionary War.","link_text":"Col. Noadiah Hooker"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"Parliament refused to make him Duke because he","body":"His descent from the Dukes of Kingston was formally established — but Parliament refused to recognize the claim because he was American. After the Revolution he became financially reduced and spent his final years working for wages at Yale, the institution his own family had helped found."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Three brothers snowbound — three sisters married","body":"Three Pierpont brothers journeying through Litchfield County stopped overnight at the Collins home in South Farms when a great storm stranded them for weeks. All three married daughters of the family: Robert married Lois Collins, his brother Evelyn married her sister Rhoda, and their brother James married a third sister."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Yale alumnus turned Yale College employee","body":"Evelyn was a Revolutionary War officer and a Yale College graduate who settled as a farmer at Litchfield Connecticut after the war. Reduced in circumstances late in life, he returned to Yale — not as alumnus but as employee — and continued in such service until his death."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Lt. Evelyn Pierpont","first_name":"Eve